Does this abort for you too?

The failing assertion is in `unlink_executor`'s `assert(executor->vm_data.valid);`. I think the assertion is just wrong. I don't see how an executor that is being unlinked should be guaranteed to be valid. Here's what happens:

```
        case _START_EXECUTOR: {
            PyObject *executor = (PyObject *)CURRENT_OPERAND0();
            #ifndef _Py_JIT
            assert(current_executor == (_PyExecutorObject*)executor);
            #endif
            assert(tstate->jit_exit == NULL || tstate->jit_exit->executor == current_executor);
            tstate->current_executor = (PyObject *)executor;
            if (!current_executor->vm_data.valid) {
                assert(tstate->jit_exit->executor == current_executor);
                assert(tstate->current_executor == executor);
                _PyFrame_SetStackPointer(frame, stack_pointer);
                _PyExecutor_ClearExit(tstate->jit_exit);   <------------ this gets called
                stack_pointer = _PyFrame_GetStackPointer(frame);
                if (true) {
                    UOP_STAT_INC(uopcode, miss);
                    JUMP_TO_JUMP_TARGET();
                }
            }
            break;
        }
```
If you look above, the branch taken is in `!current_executor->vm_data.valid`. That means the current executor is not valid, and we clear it. Yet when we clear it, we assert it's valid??? Seems like a buggy assertion. @markshannon WDYT?
